(410, 'truck_locally', 'truck_local.png', 1, 'Truck Locally', 'The Bloomberg administration and some Manhattan officials and residents are at loggerheads over whether a recycling center should be built on the Gansevoort peninsula in Hudson River Park. Much of the city''s recyclables are handled in neighborhoods in the outer boroughs. The administration says that taking recyclables to local stations in each of the boroughs, including Manhattan, would consume less energy and  reduce pollution.', 0, 0, 450, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 2.53, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:31:18'),
(410, 'truck_nj', 'truck_nj.png', 2, 'Truck to Jersey', 'Most of Manhattan''s recyclables stay on the sanitation truck that collects them at curbside until they reach New Jersey, where they are processed. This accounts for an estimated 700,000 truck trips a year.', 0, 0, 455, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 6.66, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:27:54'),
(410, 'truck_outerborough', 'truck_williamsburg.png', 3, 'Truck to Outer Borough', 'Trucking recyclable materials to the outer boroughs,advocates contend, unfairly burdens certain neighborhoods with the city''s trash as well as the health and environmental hazards that go along with it. Many of these centers are concentrated in poorer residential neighborhoods.', 0, 0, 457, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 11.4, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 12:23:14'),
(450, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 460, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(455, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 510, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(457, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 560, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-08 15:15:29'),
(460, 'barge_citywide', 'barge_citywide.png', 1, 'Barge to Citywide Center', 'The city has established a 20-year contract with the Sims Group to build a large citywide recycling center in Sunset Park. The citywide facility costs an estimated $45 million and will create about 160 construction jobs and 100 permanent jobs. Putting materials on a barge and sending them down the East River produces fewer emissions in the city than shipping the material on trucks.', 0, 0, 501, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 6.4, '2007-11-12 20:40:56'),
(460, 'barge_outside_city', 'barge_outside_city.png', 2, 'Barge to Center Outside City', 'The city plans on eliminating about 55,000 vehicle miles by transporting recyclables by barge or rail. But in transporting recyclables to a processing center outside of the city via barge, New York is still exporting its waste.', 0, 0, 500, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 5.54, '2007-11-12 20:40:56'),
(460, 'truck_verzano', 'truck_verrazano.png', 3, 'Truck to Citywide Center', 'Trucking recyclables over bridges and through the boroughs, some environmentalists argue, pollutes residential neighborhoods and creates health problems, like asthma. The city wants to phase out trucking from borough to borough but has not yet met that goal.', 0, 0, 501, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:40:56'),
(500, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 510, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-07 19:01:55'),
(501, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 515, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 16:08:37'),
(510, 'barge_ocean', 'barge_ocean.png', 1, 'Barge to Asia', 'Most of the city''s recycled raw materials are exported. Because of a shortage of forestry resources in countries like China, Japan and Taiwan, paper exports from the United States are highly desirable. The largest export from the Port of New York and New Jersey is scrap paper. International ship emissions account for more than 14 percent of nitrogen emissions and over 16 percent of sulfur emissions worldwide. Today''s large cargo ships can release as much pollution in one hour as 350,000 current cars.', 0, 0, 660, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 13584, '2007-11-14 11:17:39'),
(510, 'barge_citywide', 'barge_citywide.png', 2, 'Manufactured in City', 'When paper is processed at a private paper-recycling center on Staten Island, the city collects taxes at almost every stage. Some claim by exporting the paper, the city loses revenue.', 0, 0, 660, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 14.218, '2007-11-12 20:40:56'),
(510, 'train_garbage', 'train_garbage.png', 3, 'Rail Throughout Country', 'Materials can also be packed in railcars and sent to manufacturers across the country. That diverts manufacturing revenues from the city. Some officials contend the cost of doing business in New York City makes it difficult to process raw materials here.', 0, 0, 660, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 383, 0, '2007-11-12 21:23:01'),
(515, 'barge_ocean', 'barge_ocean.png', 1, 'Barge to Asia', 'Most of the city''s recycled raw materials are exported. Because of a shortage of forestry resources in countries like China, Japan and Taiwan, paper exports from the United States are highly desirable. The largest export from the Port of New York and New Jersey is scrap paper. International ship emissions account for more than 14 percent of nitrogen emissions and over 16 percent of sulfur emissions worldwide. Today''s large cargo ships can release as much pollution in one hour as 350,000 current cars.', 0, 0, 660, 0, 0, 0, 'sorted', 0, 0, 0, 13584, '2007-11-14 11:17:40'),
