(670, 'truck_verrazano', 'truck_verrazano.png', 1, 'Take it to Fresh Kills', 'The former landfill on Staten Island that was closed in 2001, Fresh Kills is one of only two man-made structures that can be seen from space. The other is the Great Wall of China. Fresh Kills is being developed as a park now.', 0, 0, 770, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 22.45, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 11:14:01'),
(670, 'marine_transfer', 'marine_transfer.png', 2, 'Truck to Station in Outer Boroughs', 'After Fresh Kills was closed in 2001, the city''s trash went to transfer stations in the Bronx or Brooklyn. The new system cost the city 50 percent more than dumping the garbage in Fresh Kills. Advocates and environmentalists claim the concentration of stations in the outer boroughs amounts to environmental discrimination.', 0, 0, 710, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 10.25, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:42:35'),
(670, 'truck_williamsburg', 'truck_williamsburg.png', 3, 'Truck it to a Local Transfer Station', 'New York City throws out enough garbage every day to fill the Empire State Building. For much of it, the first stop is at a station where it can be transferred to a railcar or barge. The city''s current plan calls for greater use of local transfer stations.', 0, 0, 710, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 5.88, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:43:29'),
(710, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 720, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-07 20:26:43'),
(720, 'landfill', 'landfill.png', 1, 'Private Landfill', 'The city throws away 24 million pounds of household trash each day, which, according to some estimates, costs about $167 per ton to send to an out-of-state landfill or incinerator. Most of the trash is trucked to landfills upstate, or to Pennsylvania, Ohio or Virginia.', 0, 0, 770, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 0, 73, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:43:29'),
(720, 'conveyer_belt', 'conveyer_belt.png', 2, 'Materials Recovery Facility', 'Instead of separating your trash into a plastic, metal, glass, paper and non-recyclable piles you could lump them all together and send them to a nearby materials recovery facility. Here the waste is passed to a private contractor and separated. Based on other models in the country, it would cost a total of $153 per ton to do this here. About 90 percent of the material that enters this type of facility, is processed and can be resold.', 0, 0, 770, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 0, 8.19, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:43:29'),
(720, 'incinerator', 'incinerator.png', 3, 'Incinerator in New Jersey', 'New York State is the top waste exporter in the country at 4.2 million tons a year. Like out of state landfills, incinerators cost the city, from curbside to export, an estimated $167 per ton. According to one estimate, Newark''s incinerator receives 1,700 tons of waste from Manhattan daily.', 0, 0, 770, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 0, 8.19, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:43:29'),
(720, 'energy_plant', 'energy_plant.png', 4, 'Waste to Energy Plant', 'While the city stopped considering a waste to energy plant after a very controversial proposal by Mayor Ed Koch in the early ''80s, plants on Long Island have proved to be successful and less environmentally costly than thought two decades ago. One in Hempstead burns 900,000 tons of garbage annually and powers itself as well as 65,000 adjacent homes. ', 0, 0, 770, 0, 0, 0, 'unsorted', 0, 8.19, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:43:29'),
(770, 'next', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 780, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-07 20:47:05'),
(780, 'next', 'next.png', 1, '', '', 0, 0, 790, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 19:04:07'),
(790, 'show_form', 'next.png', 1, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 790, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-13 21:44:20'),
(9030, 'plastic_reuse', 'plastic_reuse.png', 2, 'Refill Use Again', 'In 2006, Americans bought 50 billion water bottles - 167 for every person in the country. About 38 billion of those bottles ended up in a landfill.', 0, 0, 9060, 0, 0, 13258, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 11:07:39'),
(9030, 'plastic_reduce', 'plastic_reduce.png', 1, 'Don''t Drink Bottled Water', 'Approximately 25 percent of all bottled water is municipal tap water. New York''s water is so pure - it originates in streams upstate - that it does not need to be filtered.  It costs 49 cents a year to use New York City tap water, while it costs $1,400 a year to purchase bottled water.', 0, 0, 9090, 0, 0, 17677, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 11:07:39'),
(9030, 'plastic_unsorted', 'plastic_unsorted.png', 2, 'Toss it in the Can', 'Nationwide, 2.5 million plastic bottles are thrown away every hour.', 0, 0, 9099, 0, 17677, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 15:38:44'),
(9030, 'plastic_sorted', 'paper_sorted.png', 1, 'Sort for Recycling', 'Nationwide, 25 percent of plastic bottles are recycled. Of all the glass, metal and plastics collected for recycling in the city, plastics make up about 13 percent. For residences, the city''s waste diversion rate for recycling is about 18 percent. The rate could be as a high as 36 percent, but 50 percent of materials that could be recycled are thrown out with the regular trash.', 0, 0, 9097, 17677, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 15:40:10'),
(9060, 'plastic_sorted', 'paper_sorted.png', 1, 'Sort for Recycling', 'Nationwide, 25 percent of plastic bottles are recycled. Of all the glass, metal and plastics collected for recycling in the city, plastics make up about 13 percent. For residences, the city''s waste diversion rate for recycling is about 18 percent. The rate could be as a high as 36 percent, but 50 percent of materials that could be recycled are thrown out with the regular trash.', 0, 0, 9096, 4420, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 15:38:44'),
(9060, 'plastic_unsorted', 'plastic_unsorted.png', 2, 'Toss it in the Can', 'Nationwide, 2.5 million plastic bottles are thrown away every hour.', 0, 0, 9095, 0, 4420, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-14 15:38:44'),
(9090, 'next', 'next.png', 1, '', '', 0, 0, 390, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:18:08'),
(9095, 'next', 'next.png', 1, '', '', 0, 0, 390, 0, 0, 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2007-11-12 20:18:08'),
